# Rule: style-system

All visual styling in this project flows through a strict design token system defined in `styles/tokens.css`.

## Token Naming Convention

Pattern: `--brand-[category]-[name]`

| Category | Examples |
|---|---|
| `--brand-color-*` | bg, surface, ink, gold, crimson, success, warning |
| `--brand-space-*` | xs (4px), sm (8px), md (16px), lg (24px), xl (40px) |
| `--brand-radius-*` | sm (6px), md (8px), lg (12px), pill (999px) |
| `--brand-font-*` | ui, mono |
| `--brand-shadow-*` | sm, md, lg |

## Hard Rules

1. **No hardcoded colors anywhere.** Use `var(--brand-color-*)`. The only exception is inside `tokens.css` itself.
2. **No hardcoded spacing values in main.css.** Use `var(--brand-space-*)`.
3. **No hardcoded border-radius values.** Use `var(--brand-radius-*)`.
4. **No new tokens without permission.** If you need a value that doesn't exist:
   - STOP
   - Ask the user: "I need a token `--brand-[category]-[name]` with value `[value]`. May I add it to tokens.css?"
   - Wait for confirmation.

## Tailwind Usage

Tailwind utility classes (loaded via CDN) are allowed but discouraged for brand styling. Use them for:
- Quick layout (flex, grid, gap) when faster than custom CSS
- One-off utilities (text-center, hidden, etc.)

Do NOT use Tailwind for:
- Colors (use brand tokens via custom CSS classes)
- Spacing on brand components
- Anything in the design reference

When in doubt, write custom CSS using brand tokens.

## CSS File Discipline

`styles/tokens.css`:
- ONLY contains `:root { --brand-* }` definitions
- ONLY contains the global reset (`* { box-sizing: border-box; }`) and base body styling
- No component-specific styles ever

`styles/main.css`:
- All component styles
- Every property value either uses a `var(--brand-*)` token, references a layout primitive (display, flex), or is a structural value (border-width 1px, transitions 200ms)
- No `!important` unless documented why
- No inline `style=""` attributes in HTML except for dynamic values (e.g., progress bar width)

## Visual Hierarchy

Match the existing Algo Pay aesthetic:
- Cream/gold/crimson palette (warm, paper-themed)
- Folder/stamp/dossier metaphors
- Subtle textures (manila paper grain on folder bodies)
- Soft shadows, never harsh
- Rounded but not bubbly (use `--brand-radius-md` as default)
